entities.name: Country
entities.description:
Confluence Documentation does mention the need for country codification based on ISO norms. ISO 3166 is the international standard for country codes, commonly used in financial systems.

I see from the wireframe that country selection is shown with country flags (for France in the example), which typically implies using standardized country codes behind the scenes. Using both alpha2Code and alpha3Code provides flexibility since:

ISO 3166 is the international standard for country codes, commonly used in financial systems. Uses three-letter or two-letter code (e.g., many financial systems)
Having both allows for more robust integration with various systems

entities.name: LegalFormType
entities.description:
1. Corporate Structure: Funds are structured as separate legal entities, typically as corporations or companies with share capital. Investors become shareholders and own shares in the fund.
Examples: SICAV (France, Luxembourg), ICAV (Ireland), Investment Company (US).

2. Contractual Structure: Funds are established through a contractual agreement between investors and a management company. Investors hold units rather than shares.
Examples: FCP (France, Luxembourg), Common Contractual Fund (CCF) in Ireland.

3. Trust Structure: Funds are created under a trust deed, where a trustee holds assets on behalf of investors (beneficiaries).
Examples: Unit Trusts (UK, Asia-Pacific), REITs (Real Estate Investment Trusts).

entities.name: Shareclass
entities.description:
A SubFund often offers multiple share classes that represent the same underlying investment portfolio but can differ in several ways:

Fee Structures: Different classes may have different management fees, performance fees, or load/entry fees
Investor Types: Some classes may be for retail investors, others for institutional investors
Currency Denomination: Different classes may be denominated in different currencies
Distribution Policy: Some classes may distribute income (dividend-paying), while others reinvest (accumulating)
Minimum Investment Amounts: Different classes may have different minimum investment thresholds

entities.name: LegalEntity
entities.description:
This is the central entity of the model representing any legal organization. It contains common attributes like:

Basic identification (id, name, LEI)
Location information (address, city, country)
Corporate structure references (directParentId, ultimateParentId)
Metadata (creationDate, lastModifiedDate, status)

entities.name: Identifier
entities.description:
"Most of the Legal entities are identified by the LEI (Legal Entity Identifier) that can all be find in the GLEIF database: https://search.gleif.org/#/search/. Issuer and Management companies always have a LEI which is a mandatory identifier for legal entities that want to buy/issue financial instruments."

The model includes this entity to store various identifier codes that might be used by different systems, regulators, or market participants to reference the same legal entity. This explains the attributes:

identifierType (what kind of identifier, e.g., LEI, BIC, CIK, etc.)
identifierValue (the actual code)
issuer (the organization that issued this identifier)
